This article describes the author's experience during the 1-year AGA Pittsburgh fellowship from 1 April 1996 to 31 March 1997. The article is focused on the work in the Musculoskeletal Research Center and the Center for Sports Medicine of the Department of Orthopedic Surgery in Pittsburgh. The author describes projects on the biomechanics of the cruciate ligaments, using robotic technology. Organizational and social aspects of the life in Pittsburgh are discussed.  
